.TH T_OPEN 3 "@PACKAGE_DATE@" "@PACKAGE@-@VERSION@" "@PACKAGE_TITLE@ Library Calls"
.\"
.\"
.SH NAME
.B t_open
\- open a transport endpoint
.\"
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B #include <xti.h>
.HP 8
.BI "int " fd " = t_open(char *" path ", int " oflag ", struct t_info *" info );
.\"
.\"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.PP
.TP
.I path
a character string specifying the path to the device to open.
.TP
.I oflag
open flags.
.TP
.I info
a pointer to a
.B t_info
structure to contain returned information about the transport provider.
.\"
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.BR t_open ()
opens a local transport endpoint and returns a file descriptor for use in
other XTI/TLI library calls as well as information about the transport provider
for the local transport endpoint.
.PP
.I path
is a
.B Linux
filesystem path to a STREAMS character special file that once opened will
provide the necessary capabilities to the XTI/TLI Library (TPI interface and
.BR timod (4)
module pushable).
.PP
.I oflag
are open flags, defined in
.BR open (2),
which are a bitwise OR of
.B O_RDWR
and any of the following flags:
.TP
.B O_RDWR
open the STREAMS character special file read-write.
XTI/TLI does not support or permit
.BR O_RDONLY " or " O_WRONLY
flags.
.TP
.BR O_NONBLOCK " or " O_NDELAY
specifies that the file is to be opened for asynchronous operation.  When
opened for asynchronous operation, XTI/TLI library calls, 
.BR t_addleaf (3),
.BR t_connect (3),
.BR t_listen (3),
.BR t_rcv (3),
.BR t_rcvconnect (3),
.BR t_rcvdis (3),
.BR t_rcvleafchange (3),
.BR t_rcvudata (3),
.BR t_rcvv (3),
.BR t_rcvv (3),
.BR t_rcvvudata (3),
.BR t_snd (3),
.BR t_sndrel (3),
.BR t_sndreldata (3),
.BR t_sndudata (3),
.BR t_sndv (3),
.BR t_sndvudata (3),
will not block and will fail, return -1 and set
.IR t_errno (3)
to
.BR TNODATA ", " TNODIS " or " TFLOW
if they would have otherwise blocked.
.TP
.BR O_NOFOLLOW
tells
.BR t_open ()
not to follow symbolic links if
.I path
is a symbolic link to a STREAMS character special file.
.PP
The other
.BR open (2)
flags,
.BR O_RDONLY ,
.BR O_WRONLY ,
.BR O_CREAT ,
.BR O_NOCTTY ,
.BR O_TRUNC ,
.BR O_APPEND ,
.BR O_SYNC ,
.BR O_DIRECTORY ,
.BR O_LARGEFILE,
are not applicable to XTI/TLI STREAMS and should not be included.
.PP
.I info
is a pointer to a
.B t_info
structure that will return protocol information about the transport service
provider associated with the local transport endpoint.
The
.B t_info
contains the same information and follows the same rules as in the
.BR t_getinfo (3)
call.
The
.B t_info
structure is formatted as follows:
.sp
.nf
\fC\s-1\
struct t_info {
    t_scalar_t addr;
    t_scalar_t options;
    t_scalar_t tsdu;
    t_scalar_t etsdu;
    t_scalar_t connect;
    t_scalar_t discon;
    t_scalar_t servtype;
    t_scalar_t flags;
};
\fR\s+1
.fi
.PP
The
.B t_info
structure contains the following members and protocol information:
.TP
.I addr
the maximum size of a transport endpoint address.  This can be used to
determine the
.I addr->maxlen
size when passing
.BR netbuf (3)
structures to XTI/TLI Library calls.
.TP
.I options
the maximum size of the options parameter.  This can be used to determine the
.I opt->maxlen
size when passing
.BR netbuf (3)
structures to XTI/TLI Library calls.
.TP
.I tsdu
the maximum size of the transport service data unit.  This can be used to
determine the
.I udata->maxlen
size when passing
.BR netbuf (3)
structures to XTI/TLI Library calls.
.TP
.I etsdu
the maximum size of the expedited transport service data unit.  This can be used to
determine the
.I udata->maxlen
size when passing
.BR netbuf (3)
structures to XTI/TLI Library calls.
.TP
.I connect
the maximum size of connection data.  This can be used to determine the
.I udata->maxlen
size when passing
.BR netbuf (3)
structures to
.BR t_connect "(3) or " t_accept (3).
.TP
.I discon
the maximum size of disconnection data.  This can be used to determine the
.I udata->maxlen
size when passing
.BR netbuf (3)
structures to
.BR t_snddis "(3) or " t_rcvdis (3),
or, when
.B T_ORDRELDATA
is set in
.IR flags ,
.BR t_sndreldata "(3) or" t_rcvreldata (3).
.RS 12
.PP
Any of the size parameters returned can also be one of the following values:
.TP
.B T_INFINITE
the size of the parameter is unlimited.
.TP
.B T_INVALID
the transport service provider has no concept of the parameter in question.
.RE
.TP
.I servtype
the service type of the underlying transport service provider.  The service
type can be one of the following values:
.RS
.TP
.B T_CLTS
connectionless transport service.
.TP
.B T_COTS
connection oriented transport service.
.TP
.B T_COTS_ORD
connection oriented transport service with orderly release.
.RE
.TP
.I flags
contains other option information about the transport service provider and may
be a bitwise OR of any of the following flags:
.RS
.TP
.B T_ORDRELDATA
when set, this flag indicates that the transport service provider will accept
data with orderly release.
.TP
.B T_SNDZERO
when set, this flag indicates that the transport service provider will accept
the transmission of zero-length data.
.TP
.B XPG4_1
when set, this flag indicates that the transport service provider supports the
XPG4 primitives
.BR T_ADDR_REQ " and " T_ADDR_ACK .
.RE
.\"
.\"
.SH "RETURN VALUE"
.PP
Upon success,
.BR t_open ()
returns a positive integer file descriptor
.I fd
and a completed
.B t_info
structure.
Upon failure,
.BR t_open ()
returns -1 and sets
.IR t_errno (3)
to an appropriate error number.
.\"
.\"
.SH ERRORS
.PP
When
.BR t_open ()
fails, it returns -1 and sets
.IR t_errno (3)
to an appropriate error number as follows:
.TP \w'[TNOTSUPPORT]\(em'u
.RB [ TBADFLAG ]
The argument
.I oflag
contains invalid flags.
.TP
.RB [ TBADNAME ]
The transport provider name (\fIpath\fR to the device) is invalid.
.TP
.RB [ TPROTO ]
A protocol error occured between the XTI/TLI library and the underlying transport provider.
.TP
.RB [ TSYSERR ]
A \fBLinux\fR system error occured and the \fBLinux\fR error number is set in \fIerrno\fR(3).
.\"
.\"
